	  When a terminal file is opened, it normally causes the
	  process to wait until	a connection is	established.  In
	  practice, user programs seldom open terminal files; they are
	  opened by _g_e_t_t_y and become standard input, output, and error
	  files	for a user.

	  The very first terminal file opened by the process group
	  leader of a terminal file, which is not already associated
	  with a process group,	becomes	the _c_o_n_t_r_o_l _t_e_r_m_i_n_a_l for that
	  process group.  The control terminal plays a special role in
	  handling quit	and interrupt signals, as discussed below.
	  The control terminal is inherited by a child process during
	  a _f_o_r_k(2).  A	process	can break this association by changing
	  its process group using _s_e_t_p_g_r_p(2).

