	  Normally, terminal input is processed	in units of lines.  A
	  line is delimited by

	     - a new-line (ASCII LF) character
	     - an end-of-file (ASCII EOT) character
	     - an end-of-line character

	  This means that a program attempting to read is suspended
	  until	an entire line has been	typed.	Also, no matter	how
	  many characters are requested	in the read call, at most one
	  line is returned.  It	is not,	however, necessary to read a
	  whole	line at	once; any number of characters may be
	  requested in a read, even one, without losing	information.

